**4. WAL Specification**

**4.1 On-Disk Format**

Each record in the WAL file:

-   INTENT (32B header + N bytes payload): intent to write N bytes at
    data_offset

-   COMMIT (32B header only): makes the preceding INTENT durable

-   ABORT (32B header only): discards the intent --- no replay

**4.2 CRC32 Coverage**

CRC32 (IEEE 802.3) covers: header bytes \[0..27\] (excluding crc32
field) + payload. Computed with crc32 field set to 0, then stored.

> crc = wal_crc32(0, &hdr, offsetof(WAL_RecordHeader, crc32));
>
> crc = wal_crc32(crc, payload, size);
>
> hdr.crc32 = crc;

**4.3 Durability Guarantees**

  ------------------------------------------------------------------------
  **Operation**         **Sync**            **Guarantee**
  --------------------- ------------------- ------------------------------
  wal_write_intent()    fdatasync() after   INTENT survives power loss
                        header+payload      before COMMIT

  wal_write_commit()    fdatasync() after   COMMIT is the durability point
                        header              

  wal_write_abort()     None                ABORT need not be durable ---
                                            no COMMIT = no replay

  snap_finalize()       fsync() after       Snapshot is atomic after
                        header write        finalize
  ------------------------------------------------------------------------

**4.4 Two-Pass Replay**

Pass 1: Scan all records sequentially. Verify CRC32 of each. Stop at
first mismatch (torn tail). Collect committed seqs into bitset.

Pass 2: Re-scan. For each INTENT whose seq is in committed set, write
payload to data_fd at data_offset.

CRC mismatch policy: treat as torn WAL tail --- stop, do not error. This
handles normal crash-mid-write scenarios.

**4.5 wal_open() --- Reopen Safety**

On reopen, scans WAL sequentially with CRC verification. Stops at first
CRC mismatch (same boundary as replay). Sets next_seq =
max_valid_seq + 1. This guarantees next_seq boundary = replay boundary
always.

**4.6 Crash Matrix**

  -----------------------------------------------------------------------
  **Crash Point**        **WAL State**       **Outcome**
  ---------------------- ------------------- ----------------------------
  Before INTENT          No INTENT on disk   No record --- clean
  fdatasync                                  

  After INTENT, before   INTENT only, no     Pass 1 skips --- not
  COMMIT                 COMMIT              replayed

  After COMMIT fdatasync INTENT + COMMIT on  Guaranteed replay ✓
                         disk                

  Mid-replay (data_fd    WAL intact          Re-replay on next boot
  write)                                     (idempotent) ✓

  Mid-INTENT write       Partial INTENT      CRC mismatch → stop at tail
  (torn)                                     ✓
  -----------------------------------------------------------------------

**5. Snapshot Integrity Specification**

**5.1 Purpose**

Snapshot is the trust anchor for recovery. It freezes committed WAL
state into a self-verifying file. Recovery: load snapshot (verify
SHA-256) → replay WAL from last_seq+1 → live.

**5.2 On-Disk Format**

56-byte header followed by N records:

  ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
  **Field**        **Offset**   **Size**   **Content**
  ---------------- ------------ ---------- ----------------------------------
  magic            0            4B         0x534E4150 (\"SNAP\")

  version          4            1B         0x01

  \_pad            5            3B         zeros

  last_seq         8            8B         Highest committed seq in this
                                           snapshot

  record_count     16           8B         Number of records in payload

  payload_hash     24           32B        SHA-256 of all record bytes
                                           (headers + data)

  \[records\]      56           variable   N × (SNAP_RecHdr 20B + payload
                                           bytes)
  ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

**5.3 Hash Coverage**

SHA-256 covers every byte after the 56B header: for each record,
hash(SNAP_RecHdr + payload bytes). Computed incrementally via
sha256_update() on each snap_append() --- no second pass needed at
finalize.

**5.4 Fail-Fast Load**

snap_load() always verifies hash before delivering any data to caller:

1.  Read header, check magic/version

2.  Verification pass: stream payload, recompute SHA-256

3.  memcmp(computed, stored) --- if mismatch: return -3 immediately (NO
    data delivery)

4.  Deliver pass: stream payload, call callback for each record

  -----------------------------------------------------------------------
  **Return      **Meaning**
  Code**        
  ------------- ---------------------------------------------------------
  0             OK --- hash verified, all records delivered

  -1            I/O error

  -2            Bad magic or version

  -3            SHA-256 mismatch --- FAIL-FAST, do not use data
  -----------------------------------------------------------------------

**6. Fabric Layer**

**6.1 BlockFabric (pogls_fabric.py)**

Memory-mapped storage backend. BLOCK_SHIFT=8 (256B per block). Provides:

-   fabric.slice(offset, length) → SliceView --- zero-copy window into
    mmap

-   fabric.snapshot() → snap_id --- O(1) root pointer swap

-   fabric.restore(snap_id) --- revert to previous state

-   Audit lane: read-only mmap view, separated from write path

**6.2 STFabricConverter (st_to_fabric.py)**

Converts .safetensors files to .pogls fabric for zero-copy tensor
loading:

-   Reads safetensors header JSON, maps each tensor to fabric blocks

-   Index Block stored at block 0 (tensor name → offset mapping)

-   FabricTensorLoader: load_tensor(name), load_layers(prefix) ---
    zero-copy from mmap

**6.3 WorkflowVersions (workflow_versions.py)**

ComfyUI workflow version manager backed by BlockFabric:

-   wv.save(name, workflow_dict) --- creates fabric snapshot, stores
    diff

-   wv.load(name) --- restores workflow from snapshot

-   wv.diff(v1, v2) --- compare two versions

-   wv.restore_previous() --- undo last save

**7. Snapshot State Machine (POGLS Core)**

These rules are invariants. Breaking any = undefined behavior.

  ------------------------------------------------------------------------
  **Rule**            **Invariant**
  ------------------- ----------------------------------------------------
  CERTIFY is one-shot PENDING→CONFIRMED_CERTIFIED ✓ \| CERTIFIED→void ✗
                      (return -3) \| double certify ✗ (return -2)

  AUTO→VOID is        CONFIRMED_AUTO→VOID ✓ \| VOID→invalidate again ✗
  one-shot            (return -3)

  Migration source    Must be CERTIFIED or PENDING --- never VOID

  CERTIFIED is        is_checkpoint_immune() = true, cannot be GC\'d
  checkpoint-immune   

  Auto-promote        When audit_health == DEGRADED, auto-promote rejected
  blocked             
  ------------------------------------------------------------------------

**8. VisualFeed Immutable Rules**

These rules must not be broken by any future code:

  -----------------------------------------------------------------------
  **Rule**              **Detail**
  --------------------- -------------------------------------------------
  ✅ Read from Audit    VisualFeed uses read-only mmap for audit context
  (PROT_READ mmap)      

  ✅ Read from Hydra    Head status via const pointer --- no write access
  (const ptr)           

  ❌ NEVER read Core    GUI/ComfyUI must not access Core mmap
  directly              

  ❌ NEVER touch        Store frame in \_last_frame, apply in main thread
  tkinter from bg       (\_poll_visual)
  thread                

  ❌ NEVER write via    Observer only --- all writes go through WAL+Hydra
  VisualFeed            
  -----------------------------------------------------------------------

**9. Build & Test Commands**

**9.1 Compile Core Tests**

> gcc pogls_snapshot.c pogls_hydra.c pogls_audit.c pogls_visual.c
> pogls_test.c -lm -o pogls_test
>
> gcc -Wall -Wextra -O2 pogls_wal.c pogls_wal_test.c -o pogls_wal_test
>
> gcc -Wall -Wextra -O2 pogls_snapshot_wal.c pogls_wal.c
> pogls_snapshot_wal_test.c -o pogls_snapshot_test

**9.2 Compile Kill-Test Binaries**

> gcc -O2 pogls_wal.c pogls_wal_worker.c -o pogls_wal_worker
>
> gcc -O2 pogls_wal.c pogls_wal_verify.c -o pogls_wal_verify

**9.3 Run Tests**

> ./pogls_test \# expect: 80/80 PASS (T09=1 SKIP expected)
>
> ./pogls_wal_test \# expect: 24/24 PASS
>
> ./pogls_snapshot_test \# expect: 37/37 PASS

**9.4 Kill Test**

> python3 pogls_kill_test.py \--worker ./pogls_wal_worker \--verify
> ./pogls_wal_verify \\
>
> \--cycles 10000 \--records 500

Expected: 10000/10000 PASS, 0 corruption, exit code 0.

